mi <- 
  read_csv("./mi.data.csv") %>% 
  janitor::clean_names() %>%
  mutate(id = as.character(id),
         sex = as.character(case_when(sex == 0 ~ "Male", 
                                      sex == 1 ~ "Female",
                                      sex == 2 ~ "Non-binary/Other")),
         pulm_adema = as.factor(pulm_adema), # levels by 0, 1 by default
         fc = factor(case_when(fc == 0 ~ "No angina pectoris",
                               fc == 1 ~ "I FC",
                               fc == 2 ~ "II FC",
                               fc == 3 ~ "III FC",
                               fc == 4 ~ "IV FC"),
                     levels = c("No angina pectoris","I FC","II FC","III FC","IV FC")),
         arr = as.factor(arr), # levels by 0, 1 by default
         diab = as.factor(diab),
         obesity = as.factor(obesity),
         asthma = as.factor(asthma),
         readmission = as.factor(readmission)
  ) %>%
  select(-id) # excluding patient id

#Centering and Scaling
set.up.preprocess <- preProcess(mi_num, method = c("center", "scale"))
#Output pre-processed values
transformed_vals <- predict(set.up.preprocess, mi_num)
mi_transformed <- bind_cols(transformed_vals, mi_not_num)
  • There are 1700 observations and 15 features (excluding patient ID) with no missing data.
  • There is a big data imbalance for readmission to the hospital within 30 days, our outcome of interest where 9.35% of the observations were readmitted (N = 159) and 90.65% were not readmitted (N = 1541).
  • Upon visual inspection, systolic blood pressure and diastolic blood pressure (both taken at intake) are very highly linearly correlated it would make sense to use just one of these features to reduce the feature space. All of the other numeric variables do not seem to be correlated.
  • The means and standard deviations for the numeric variables in our dataset are quite different. Centering and scaling are performed, and the resulting dataset is mi_transformed.

1. Elastic Net Logistic Regression.

# Regularized (elastic net) logistic regression
set.seed(100)
train_control <- trainControl(method="cv", number = 10, sampling = "up")
logistic_reg <- train(readmission ~., data = training, 
                      method = "glmnet", family = "binomial",
                      trControl = train_control, tuneLength=10)
logistic_reg$bestTune
##    alpha     lambda
## 23   0.3 0.01004879

Up-sampling is used to address the outcome imbalance in our data. After performing a logistic regression with elastic net regularization, it turns out that the best tuning parameters for alpha and lambda are 0.3 and 0.0100488, respectively.

2. Single Classification Tree.

set.seed(100)
train_control <- trainControl(method="cv", number = 10, sampling = "up")

The single classification tree identifies a complexity parameter cp that is equal to 0.022.

In creating the single classification tree, up-sampling was used to account for the imbalance in data. It turns out that the tree is only 60.03% accurate and can be improved upon using a random forest algorithm.

The classification tree identifies white blood cell counts wbc, age, and systolic blood pressure sbp to be the most important features for predicting hospital readmission within 30 days.

3. Random Forest.

set.seed(100)
train_control <- trainControl(method="cv", number = 10, sampling = "up")
mtry.vals<-c(ncol(training)-1, sqrt(ncol(training)-1), 0.5*ncol(training)-1)

mtry.grid<-expand.grid(.mtry=mtry.vals)
rf <- train(readmission ~., 
            importance = TRUE, trControl = train_control,
            data=training, method="rf", metric="Accuracy", 
            tuneGrid=mtry.grid, ntree=100)
rf$bestTune
##   mtry
## 2  6.5

In creating the random forest using up-sampling to account for the imbalance in data, the best tuning parameter for the number of features eligible for each split in the tree mtry is 6.5.

Random forest classification results and predictions.

rf$finalModel$confusion
##      0    1 class.error
## 0 1065   14  0.01297498
## 1    0 1079  0.00000000
# Plotting the variable importance
plot(varImp(rf))

varImpPlot(rf$finalModel)

After applying the random forest model back to the training dataset, we see it has an prediction accuracy of 99.35%.

It also identifies white blood cell counts wbc, age, and erythrocyte sedimentation rate esr to be the most important and influential variables in predicting hospital readmission within 30 days. The least influential variables for prediction are arr presence of arrhythmia, sex on the Non-binary/Other level, and fcIV functional class IV of angina pectoris in the last year.

Final Model.

My final model is the random forest. Although it is not as interpretable as a single classification tree nor as flexible as logistic regression, the accuracy of 99.35% blows the accuracies of 61.38% and 60.03% for the logistic regression and single classification tree out of the water.

# Making predictions
rf_testing <- predict(rf, testing, type="prob")
pred_binary <- 
  rf_testing %>%
  select("1") %>%
  rename(Yes = "1") %>%
  mutate(classification = as.factor(ifelse(Yes > 0.5, 1, 0)))

# Printing the confusion matrix
results_test <- confusionMatrix(pred_binary$classification, testing$readmission, positive = "1")

After applying the random forest model to the testing dataset, we find that it is 89.98% accurate in predicting hospital readmission status, with a sensitivity and specificity of 0% and 99.13%, respectively.

Although this model is very accurate, the sensitivity is especially low. This could be another issue with the imbalance in the data where the random forest is not classifying those who truly are admitted to the hospital within 30 days accurately. This issue is also clinically significant because we would want to correctly identify those patients who are readmitted to the hospital within 30 days, because those cases of more severe myocardial infarction would probably be more likely to be readmitted after discharge.
